EVENT 1 RECAP
…
Day one of competition is always the most nerve racking for me.

As we went to get fitted for our bikes I was told I would need to wait for the girls to finish in order to get a medium bike. They only had a couple bikes and that went to the athletes in the first line. As I sat there watching everyone warm up while I waited for a bike I could see the girls going and some people crashing. I made a game time decision to go up to a bigger bike so I would have time to warm up, size the bike, and not risk anything being broken on it from the aggressive biking in the women’s heat 🤪.

Once I was fitted for my bike we were directed to the start line. I remember looking at another competitor telling them I think I may throw up. He said let it out…As we got to the start line I just let it fly between me and another guy🤮….That made me feel much better and took the nausea away minutes before the event. 

3.2.1 and it was off to the races. I knew if you did not get out it would be next to impossible to catch back up and make moves with heats of 40. The start of the event reminded me of times when I was a kid and we would ram tires from behind trying to knock your siblings down. The first lap was insane and spiked your heart rate up. All I could think about was maintain….and avoid the crashes. 

Each lap got slightly better but I found trying to ride with someone made the time go by faster and you could push each other to hold off the guys behind us. 

I had two spots on the track that I tried to make a move…one was where my family was standing cheering…all the extra motivation. The other was running with the bike. This made the loop seem way faster and kept me awake.

Overall finished 11th in the event…which I felt pretty good about for a long endurance event and I avoided the crashes 😅

📸 @furyphotography

EVENT 2 RECAP
…
Pig chipper 🐖 
This was probably one of my favorite workouts when it got released. I thought it had a little bit of something for everyone in it. 

Walking out to the field I knew it was going to be a complete different workout….it turned into who was able to recover from the bike in event 1.

3.2.1 and it was a race to the pig. I grabbed the pig and started flipping. I planned on excelling through the back half of the workout but after 1 flip it felt way lighter than last year. That moment I made the decision to really throttle into the front half of the workout. 

Everything was going according to plan until I hit the wallballs. My original goal was 2-3 sets. That slowly dropped to reps of 10-15. I had the lead up until that point. I remember looking at the big screen thinking the lead was going to slowly disappear. Apparently I was staring at the screen more than I thought because my fiancé @kaylalatini asked me after the event why I kept staring at the leaderboard. 

I finished the wallballs and started the back half of the workout. I closed my eyes and just held on for dear life on the gymnastics.

When I got back to the pig, I saw people slowly closing in and just started to flip as fast as I could. After the 3rd flip I missed a rep…pushed the pace too hard. I rested a few moments to get my grip and arms back and had to grind out the last 7. 

Finished the event winning the heat hoping I would hold the top spot….last heat went and I finished with a 4th. Overall proud of the performance and felt like I was able to execute as best as I could. 

📸 @furyphotography
